Problem Set 7-1

Problem 1

A cantilever shaft is made of a carvon steel bar and is loaded by a force, PP.
(a) Find the vertical displacement of point CC.

At BCBC

\begin{split}
M_{BC} &= Px &\implies \frac{\partial M_{BC}}{\partial P} &= x \\\
V &= P &\implies \frac{\partial V}{\partial P} &= 1
\end{split}
\begin{split}
M_{BC} &= Px &\implies \frac{\partial M_{BC}}{\partial P} &= x \\\
V &= P &\implies \frac{\partial V}{\partial P} &= 1
\end{split}

At ABAB

\begin{split}
M_{AB} &= Px &\implies \frac{\partial M_{AB}}{\partial P} &= x \\\
V &= P &\implies \frac{\partial V}{\partial P} &= 1 \\\
T &= PL &\implies \frac{\partial T}{\partial P} &= L
\end{split}
\begin{split}
M_{AB} &= Px &\implies \frac{\partial M_{AB}}{\partial P} &= x \\\
V &= P &\implies \frac{\partial V}{\partial P} &= 1 \\\
T &= PL &\implies \frac{\partial T}{\partial P} &= L
\end{split}

The vertical deflection at CC:= \delta_{i} = \sum_{i} \frac{\partial U}{\partial P_{i}}\delta_{i} = \sum_{i} \frac{\partial U}{\partial P_{i}}.
Therefore,

\begin{split}
\delta_{i} &= \sum_{i} \frac{\partial U}{\partial P_{i}} \\\
 &\equiv \frac{1}{EI}\Biggl[ \int_{0}^{L} Px(x)dx + \int_{0}^{L}Px(x)dx \Biggr] + \frac{1}{GJ}\int_{0}^{L}PL(L)dx \\\
 &= \frac{2}{3}\frac{PL^{3}}{EI} + \frac{PL^{3}}{GJ}
\end{split}
\begin{split}
\delta_{i} &= \sum_{i} \frac{\partial U}{\partial P_{i}} \\\
 &\equiv \frac{1}{EI}\Biggl[ \int_{0}^{L} Px(x)dx + \int_{0}^{L}Px(x)dx \Biggr] + \frac{1}{GJ}\int_{0}^{L}PL(L)dx \\\
 &= \frac{2}{3}\frac{PL^{3}}{EI} + \frac{PL^{3}}{GJ}
\end{split}



Problem 2

Equilibrium


\begin{split}
\sum M_{D} = 0 &:= C_{x} = \frac{3}{2}P \\\
\sum F_{x} = 0 &:= D_{x} = -C_{x} \\\
\sum F_{y} = 0 &:= D_{y} = P
\end{split}
\begin{split}
\sum M_{D} = 0 &:= C_{x} = \frac{3}{2}P \\\
\sum F_{x} = 0 &:= D_{x} = -C_{x} \\\
\sum F_{y} = 0 &:= D_{y} = P
\end{split}

By employing the Method of Joints:


Joint A


\begin{split}
\sum F_{y} &= F_{AB}(\frac{4}{5}) - P \\\
\sum F_{x} &= F_{AB}(\frac{4}{5}) - F_{AD}
\end{split}

Joint D
\begin{split}
\sum F_{y} &= D_{y} - F_{BD}(\frac{4}{5}) \\\
F_{BD} &= \frac{5}{4}P
\end{split}
\begin{split}
\sum F_{y} &= D_{y} - F_{BD}(\frac{4}{5}) \\\
F_{BD} &= \frac{5}{4}P
\end{split}


